segments.text: And he decided he was going to get out.
But what happened then was that Robert Kennedy said he was going to get in.
And then those dumbass eastern liberals, they all said, well, this is just great.
We're going to go with Bobby, and that's going to take care of this problem.
And I said, bullshit, and came home.
Because Jack Kennedy and Bobby Kennedy are just mainstream.
I mean, they just got a different notion than the right wing of the Republicans about how to manipulate power to hold things together.
But Jack Kennedy and others were involved in that war and in racism and all those things just as heavily as any right-wing redneck or financier.
Okay.
So we came close.
At any rate, I never was going to ask people to vote for me.
All I was going to do was get on TV and say, here's a spot we wanted to show y'all.
That's why I'm running for governor.
I'm not asking you to vote for me, but I wish you'd watch this spot.
And then we were going to run those things.
So that's as far as that went.
A very interesting thing happened right after that when I came back.
I'll just mention, I'm having fun on talking about this part of it.
That was in the spring, and of course everybody's trying to figure out what we're going to do next that could have some effect and put some pressure on.
And I traveled with the guy who was the SDS regional organizer at that time, and we went to a number of different campuses around the state.
was the heaviest in political activity as far as New Left, anti-war, civil rights movement type stuff.
But we went to a number of the other campuses and spent about two weeks on the road.
And what I found out was that a whole lot of those campuses had people on them that really wanted to become active and just would like some help and some ideas about what to do.
They wanted draft counseling information.
They wanted anti-war information, civil rights, a whole ball of wax.
And a whole lot of them were very isolated.
And the campuses were very narrow and tight, prudish-minded as far as what the administration and the boards of regents or the governing boards would like to tolerate.
And of course, a lot of them used to like to come to Austin because Austin was the most progressive and had the most open view about what life was about and how people ought to enjoy it.
So what we decided to do was put together a traveling roadshow that summer.
that would go around to a number of these areas.
And we did.
It was a multimedia show.
It had a great name.
It was called Mother's Grits, Austin Anarcho-Terrorist, New Left Beaten Evangelical Traveling Troop.
It was a great bunch of people.
Each place we went, there'd be between 15 and 30 or 35 of them, just men and women.
It's what I call a multimedia project.
We used theater.
We had music.
We had draft counseling.
We had open forum.
We had some speeches.
There was a man named Larry Caroline who was very...
very active and a very articulate, forceful speaker who had a big impact during that time.

He was a professor out here at the University of Texas in the philosophy department, and he's the one who made a number of very good revolutionary statements and got in major trouble with Frank Irwin and the jackasses who ran the university and most of the educational institutions in Texas.
But Larry was a
very well educated, very articulate, very popular.
And he came to a number of those events.
When we did five of them, we did one of them at A&M.
And it was delicious.
God almighty.
See, the people that did that from Austin, they really believed in what they were doing.
And they really worked hard at trying to communicate.
So we knew when we went into these areas that there were going to be confrontation.
The tension was there.
We knew it was going to be there.
What I did, I helped organize it.
I did what they call the advance work.
I'd go into a community a week or ten days, two weeks ahead of time to find the area where we could have it.
Of course, none of them, the churches or the schools, there ain't no buildings available.
So we found that out in a hurry.
I am a lawyer, I was a lawyer, and one place they cannot stop you from having it is a public park.
So we'd go into these places and we'd find a public park that would be suitable.
Of course, we'd find some local people, usually there were two or three or four or five, sometimes more than that, who were willing to work with us and be identified with it.
And then I'd work with the local media and I'd go to the sheriff and I'd tell him, you know, this is what's going to happen.
You know, like it were the shit, but fuck you.
We're going to do it anyway.
And and I didn't come on that abrasive to start with, but I didn't take any shit off any of the guy that I remember the sheriff over in Commerce, Texas.
We went to we went to Commerce, East Texas State.
We went to Denton, North Texas State.
We went to A&M at Bryan College Station.
We went to San Marcos and we went to Dallas.
And, of course, Commerce was the most redneck ignorant goddamn bunch of office holders that I ran across.
The second day I was there, I went to see the sheriff and told him what we were going to do.
We were going to be down in that park a week from tonight, and we were going to have our own portable generator there, and we were going to have microphones.
And I laid it out.
We were all very honest and straightforward.
And I said, you mean a lot to me.
probably don't like our politics and what we believe in, but so be it.
We're going to talk to the people in this area.
We know that a lot of them do agree with us, and more of them would like information, and we're going to do it.

And I forget the exact sequence, but at one point he said, he said, you come over here and do that, and he said, I'm going to throw you so far back in jail, they'll have to pipe your civil rights to you.
And I said...
You go right ahead, you son of a bitch.
I've got a law firm in Dallas and one in Houston, the ACLU, that's ready to put Commerce, Texas on the map.
And you better go talk to your bosses and the commissioner's court and the county judge and see if that's what they want to happen to Commerce, Texas.
If they do, well, we'll get it on.
So, and they backed off.
I mean, that was interesting.
But when we went to A&M,
There were some people there.
There was an economics professor and his wife.
Since they moved to Austin, several years, a number of years ago, moved to Austin.
At any rate, we set up out there in that field, dedicated parkland.
I mean, they couldn't stop us.
And we had a big crowd, I don't know, 600 to 1,000 people.
And there was a lot of hostility.
And in our theater troupe, about two-thirds women and a third men.
And the women were very talented.
And more than that, they were very adept at disarming hostility.
And so they helped break the ice and ease the tension as far as at least getting the show off the ground.
And we kind of went through the
through the general routine.
And what we found was that we had one of our best occasions there at A&M because the Aggies, they had never, ever been allowed to speak on a microphone.
And what we would do, you know, Caroline, our main speaker, would give our statement about the war and what ought to be done and how individuals ought to relate to that.
And then we'd have an open forum and anybody that wanted to talk could come up and talk
with the general understanding that you say whatever you want to, cuss, do whatever you're going to do, but you've got to do it within two or three minutes.
And god damn, they lined up.
It's been an hour and a half, I know, with people who never had a chance on campus to express themselves.
about the war in Vietnam and about civil rights and all the big issues of the day and all the big conflicts that were going on.
And it worked out fine because what you generally find out, if people will be honest, is that you've got a lot more agreement than you've got disagreement if you get past certain hurdles.
Nearly everybody will agree they don't like poverty and they don't like hunger and they don't like people to die from bad health practices.
And then at least you got the possibility then to talk about what you're going to do about it.
Is this system here going to do anything about it or do you have to do something else?
But the A&M trip worked out well.
And that Mother's Grits Roadshow went five different places that summer and addressed audiences a total of probably a couple of thousand at the most.
One of our larger crowds was at A&M in Commerce.
Had a pretty big crowd at Dallas and Lee Park, I think it was.
But a lot of the most active people off of those campuses then either formed local groups and began to do things or a lot of them moved to, they dropped out of school.
They moved to Austin, they moved to San Francisco, they moved to Madison.
They got active, they started doing things.
which is what it was all about.
Do you want to get back to more of this?
I'm digressing so much, I don't know how much we're covering.
You been having a good time?
Who's winning today?
What organizations were active in Austin in the 60s, and then what organizations were you active in?
Yeah, okay.
The first thing we should remember is a lot of organizations overlap.
They're used for different purposes.
You find a lot of the same people in several different organizations.
And you use, not in any manipulative way, because we were honest with the media, but you use whatever seems to be the proper structure at the time.
There was the SDS, Students for Democratic Society, at the University of Texas, and it was also an off-campus group.
Within SDS, there was a group called the Friends of Progressive Labor.
Popple, F-O-P-L, which is a Maoist-oriented, pseudo-Maoist, I think, because I admire Mao, and I think he would disown this bunch.
I mean, they really had their head up their ass.
But they were a Maoist group that had a national party, which was a disciplined Marxist-Leninist party.
Are you familiar with...
They have a...
They believe in secrecy and they're a whole bunch of...
They're contrary to what I think of as the New Left and what I was a part of.
The Trotskyists, what do they call it?
The Socialist Workers Party of America.
There's three or four socialist parties in the United States and I never have gotten them all straight.
A lot of different splinter groups.
The Communist Party, I think they had two or three members here in Austin.
Not anything like the media, but I think there were two or three that were party members.
And as I say, they were very tame.
They didn't even come close.
We had one group who were anarchists, what I call anarchists.
A lot of artists and musicians and dancers and highly talented people that were influenced by the people in New York City.
And they were called up against the wall, motherfucker.
That was a saying in New York City, and it spawned groups all across the
the country called up against the wall motherfuckers.
And they did a lot of guerrilla theater, did a lot of confrontational work.
And they were your local man.
To me, they were an organization.
According to some academic theories, they would never be called an organization, because they wasn't no leader.
They wasn't nothing except they got together when they felt like it and did something.

The American Friends Service Committee, that's the Quaker group, has always been heavily involved in progressive anti-war, civil rights movement, prisoners, Amnesty International, which is very prominent still today.
Those are some of the groups.
The Farm Workers Union was here in Austin, and that was a group who
made the initial efforts in the Rio Grande Valley to organize farm workers.

Originally, they were associated with Chavez, the guy from California, but there were conflicts with that California Chavez group about whether or not the Texas people could strike, and the California people didn't want them to because they wanted to focus on where they felt they could do best.
I won't get into all those arguments, but the Texas people wanted to strike, did.
That caused a split.
and the farm workers, so there was the Texas Farm Workers Union, but they were part of the local group.

The black groups here in Austin, there's an Urban League, which, and the NAACP, Southern Christian Leadership Conference, SCLC, and at one time there was some SNCC, the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee.
Now the Urban League is a very establishment organization,
Uncle Tom, property, conscious, oriented bunch of upper affluent, a few, there's not many black folks.
The NAACP in Austin, it's not true nationally, because nationally it's strictly a middle of the road to the right organization, very conservative.
Always believes in going to court and seeing if you can't do something at the ballot box.
I mean, they're not major...
They were not major forces in the Civil Rights Movement.
They didn't believe in confrontation, and they didn't push things.
Martin Luther King's outfit, Southern Christian Leadership Conference, and SNCC, and CORE, we had a CORE group, Congress of Racial Equality.
They pushed things.
And most people don't realize that the main impetus in the Black Civil Rights Movement, just like in the movement...
in the United States overall at that time was the young people.
So it was SNCC who pushed things.
Martin Luther King was the most articulate speaker, but H.R.F.
Brown, Stokely Carmichael, a number of those folks, along with a lot of the young people, really pushed things in the black movement.
In fact, no doubt in my mind, they are the ones who, within the black community, put the pressure on Martin Luther King,
finally made him take a stand on the Vietnam War.
For a long period of time, he would not do it.
He would not come down against it, figuring he wanted to concentrate on civil rights.
But the black young people said, no, bullshit.
They're killing us.
They're dragging us off to war.
And you say we're not going to say anything about it.
You're not going to be a leader much longer, old man, if you don't start saying the right thing.
And they're the ones who did the preliminary work for a lot of the
King demonstrations.
Most people don't understand that, too.
It's just like the way the labor union movement was organized in the United States.
Most of that work was done in the 20s and 30s by the radicals, the wobblies, the communists.
It was not done by AFL-CIO types.
I mean, it was done by people who had major intense convictions about what was right and what was wrong and were willing to get hurt and die for it.
And a lot of them did.
At any rate, to go down those groups.
Now, what else did we have?
What were you active in?
Well, the only one that I continuously identified with was SDS.
And SDS went through a progression.
If you've studied much history, you don't know it.
It finally became sectarian and began to close up.
What I always liked about it, it was very open, very honest.
Spent whatever amount of time was necessary in meetings or otherwise to let everybody speak their view and to hash things out.
It did not go on strict parliamentary procedure.
We vote and cut off debate and that kind of shit.
That didn't happen.
You might spend five hours
but when you finished, you were either going to have a consensus or you weren't going to do anything, which is a way for humans to approach problems.
At any rate, SDS was later, because of sexism and because of the way men treated women and because of sectarianism, some of those rigid groups gained too much control in national SDS.
I never did identify that much with National SDS.
I don't think most of the people in Texas or Berkeley or Madison, the major areas, did either.
I mean, SDS was a lot of anarchist tendencies there.
I mean, control close to where you live and what you want to do and what you're willing to do.
Don't write a paper off 500 miles from here and tell me I'm supposed to go do this when you don't know what I'm doing.
So SDS, of course, earlier, back when I was a liberal, still believed that electoral politics might offer.
I was a member of the Texas Democratic Coalition.
I quit.
The last time I voted was when Lyndon became president.
I quit voting.
I knew that was too much shit.
It wouldn't do any good.
Would you have classified yourself as a liberal in the early 60s or later as a radical?
No.
In 1960, I first worked for the man who ran for governor, and then I worked for the guy who was the United States senator, and then I was with that state liberal organization.
So I was a Democrat, liberal Democrat in 1960 until right after Jack Kennedy got killed.
And of course, I was learning all the time, particularly from the black people,
that the system wasn't working and wasn't going to work as far as the basic stuff that bothered me, racism and poverty and later on the war.
It just wasn't going to change unless you made change.
So in 1964, when Lennon cut off the money and that organization fell apart, I became heavily involved in the Civil Rights Movement.
And during that time, I was fortunate.
I got to meet Martin Luther King.
They paid my way to come over to
at their national convention at the Southern Leadership Conference to give a speech about how we did the block worker program in Texas.
And I got to meet him and a bunch of the people who were national figures.
Of course, that was a top-heavy, preacher-oriented, middle-class organization as far as the people that were well-known.
The ones who did the dangerous, heavy-duty work were younger, and you wouldn't know their names.
And so I guess during that, and then I guess about a two-year period there, I would have considered myself a radical.
I was a liberal Democrat, and then I was a radical.
And then as I became more aware, and it was around the SDS New Left people, a lot of them were very well-read and educated, and not with degrees.
And I don't mean that, but I mean, they'd done a lot of intensive work.
I learned a lot more.
And out of all those discussions,
I became what I think of, what I still am today, which is revolutionary.
I believe it takes basic change.
And unfortunately, I believe in our society, American United States society, that that's not going to be accomplished by electoral change.
Big interests are not going to permit you to take away all their property because you vote.
And that bullshit, anybody that's naive and thinks that, they'll shoot you first.
So from about 1967, 68 on, I considered myself a revolutionary.
And that's by my own definition.
I don't belong to any, never have belonged to any organized, structured, disciplined group.
In fact, it's contrary to my politics.
I'm kind of an anarchist.
libertarian revolutionary, that's the way I describe myself.
So would you like to define the term radical or the term revolutionary?
Do I like the term?
What term would you like to define or both?
Oh.
Because you don't really count yourself as a radical.
Well, I think a revolutionary is a radical, but a radical is not necessarily a revolutionary.
Are you familiar with Saul Alinsky?
He's a man who organized a bunch of projects that have continued to exist, starting up in Chicago and Rochester, New York.
And there's a bunch of them outgrowth here
Texas, you familiar with Acorn?
Now that's an Alinsky type organization, Saul Alinsky.
A lot of the people that run that outfit got their training and their principles from this Saul Alinsky.
Now they're radicals.
They don't think necessarily that a revolution, a major confrontation is necessary to attain what they want to attain.
They go in more for holding meetings and deciding what needs to be done in a small, defined area such as a neighborhood or a city.
We need this kind of electricity.
We need this kind of roadway.
They don't work as much on what I think of as interrelationships.
If you really understand power, you know you're not going to get as limited on what they're going to give you.
but they believe that it's worthwhile and those things can be obtained, and that's what they want to do.
I personally think Solomonsky is highly manipulative.

I think that he knows that the frustrations that occur in people after you spend three or four or five years of doing that type of organizing and work, and all you do is get bits and pieces and they throw you a bone occasionally, but you never see the major changes.
What happens is people become more radical.
They either do that or drop out.
Well, I think what he is is an old leftist.
I think he's probably 50 years ago some secretary and maybe had been a Communist Party member.
I don't know if he was or not, but they're highly manipulative people.
I don't know if you're familiar with them or not, but don't ever trust anybody who's a party member of them.
of the sectarian mass group.
They tell you what they think they need to tell you.
They're like liberal democratic politicians.
They do what's necessary to get you to do what they want you to do.
They did a lot of anti-war work, and they had a group called Fuck the Army, FTA.
And they'd go around to different spots to help get information out.
Of course, Jane found a major drawing card, Tom Hayden, to a lesser extent.
He was one of the national founders and writers of the Port Huron Statement, which is the early basic document of SDS.
which is a pretty good liberal democratic type analysis of society at that time.
At any rate, we had them come here to Austin.
And up here at Fort Hood, which is a major military installation, they trained army troops and others.
We had a coffee house, military organizing coffee house, called the Oleo Strut, which is named after a part of a helicopter.
train helicopter units out there.
And we had Fonda and Hayden work out there and go out there and, of course, attracted large, lots of people, lots of GIs who were anti-war, who most of them stoned out.
I mean, God, the dilemma those men were in was a lot of them, they're going through training, they know where they're going, and they don't like it.
They're afraid they're going to get killed.
They're afraid they're going to do something they don't want to do.
You know, what the hell am I going to do?
At any rate, they both spoke out there.
We had them here in Austin.
We finally found a place to... We had one on-campus event.
No, we didn't.
We couldn't find an on-campus site.
We finally used the back room of Schultz's Beer Garden, which is a very famous Austin tavern.
And they made that back room available to us.
I helped organize it.
I went and talked to the owner.
And the owner was a guy named Larry Bales, who was in the Texas House of Representatives at that time.
A lot of guts.
I guess he was the most so-called liberal Democrat in the Texas House of Representatives in that year.
The Texas legislature, I think, passed a resolution in both houses, something like 500 to 1.
that Jane Fonda was an asshole and a communist and bad news and don't come and all that.
But Larry went ahead and let us use the place.
We had a standing room on the pack crowd.
And then we also went on campus.
But we never could use a major facility.
I don't know whether this happened at A&M.
I imagine it.

I'm damn sure it has happened, but here at the University of Texas, they've really tightened up since the 60s and early 70s about campus regulations, what they will permit and will not permit, according to their legal theory, most of which is unconstitutional, but then you've got to go through the bullshit of taking it to court.
It takes a long time to bring those court fights.
About where you can meet, where you can talk,
Supposedly you have free speech and free assembly, but you don't.
And since the 60s and early 70s, they put in major changes in the regulations to try to tighten that up.
The walls you see out here at the university campus around the stone walls around, those were put up because of the demonstrations.
It makes it much easier from their point of view
for crowd control to have a three- or four- or five-foot wall that somebody has to come over before they can have one coffin handle a much larger area than if it's all flat.
So a lot of our landscaping was done for crowd control purposes, to try to shut off the university, which is, of course, contrary to the basic notion of what a university is about.
It ought to be an integral part of the community
not walls around it.

Okay, I don't want to digress any longer, but there was a very effective GI organizing effort going on here and at Fort Hood, and then the Fort Hood people would come to Austin and join in with what we were doing, and we'd go help them.
And we had law firms here in Austin, one big law firm called a movement law firm that would do all that heavy-duty political work because the people really believed in it, the lawyers did.

and do it on a free basis, on a mandatory free basis, because we'd all get involved in trying to raise the money and get the evidence together and do all the shit work and leg work that it required to do whatever it was legally we were trying to do.
And a lot of the CO, conscientiously subjected cases, a lot of the military cases where they were trying to kick people out of the military without
due process and without certain benefits.
A lot of the lawyers here helped out on it.
Okay, what have we got?
What's next?
Okay.
What were the major incidents, quote unquote, in Austin?
Just a few major ones.
Yeah, just a few because I made a collage one time when I was drinking a lot and had about a week and I had a board about the size of this window and
And I made up cards and used clippings and pictures and a bunch of shit that I had.
I had 60 or 70 different items on that board of things I was involved in.
Maybe a third or a fourth of them are what you would probably call major.
The big one as far as longer term conflict with the university was the Chuck Wagner case.
And I was heavily involved in that one.
We effectively won that over a period of time.
I mean, nobody once read it.
And we did exert considerable pressure on the university.
And we were effective in using the case itself as an organizing device to reach more people about the issues that were involved.
A lot of good lawyers around the state helped out, volunteered to work on that case.
And it had the district attorneys and the district judges who were sitting in their britches, because they were very heavy duty lawyers.
And we were on the side of the angels as far as the constitutional legalities go.
There were some factual problems, but not major ones.
Mario Maverick, Jr., out of San Antonio, which is a very prominent name, was involved.
Warren Burnett, who's probably the best trial lawyer and one of the best in the United States out of Odessa, was involved.
Cameron Cunningham, Jim Simons, and Brady Coleman from here in Austin.
Sam Houston Clinton, who's now one of the judges on the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, the top criminal court.
He was one of the defense lawyers, one of our lawyers.
Dave Richards out of Dallas.
the biggest labor law firm in Dallas.
Bob Hall out of Houston, the biggest labor law firm in Houston.
And of course, that means they're among the biggest in the country, because those are the laborers, and they're very good lawyers.
The Chuckwagon case, of course, that involved whether the university could really crack down on

shutting off that the university facilities to what they think of as outsiders people who will not enroll dues paying students and of course now some people might buy that definition but we didn't and i don't a university is an open institution as far as i'm concerned particularly when society's money pays for it don't tell me that
I've got to pay tuition to be able to go talk to a student or a teacher over there or read a book.
Fuck you.
At any rate, that was a major one.
We did another major event.
It wasn't a demonstration.
Is that what you want, demonstrations?
We held a legal conference at Wembley, which this is all well documented in the Texas Observer.
And I helped organize that, where we had
a bunch of trial lawyers and plaintiff's lawyers and liberal lawyers from around the state who came and spent several days at a guest ranch that we rented up at Wimberley.
We brought in speakers.
Bill Cussler, you know William Cussler, who's defended the Chicago 7.
He's one of the lawyers who defended the Chicago 7.
Charles Gary, who defended Angela Davis, the Black Panther woman, he was there from San Francisco.
We had a number of outside speakers, and then we had a lot of workshops and discussions between movement activists and lawyers about what was going on and what was needed.
Traditionally, the legal profession does not want to give up control of a legal case.
In other words, if a lawyer's hired to
pursue a certain case, he wants all the control about what's going to be said and done and not done in the courtroom.
Well, that is basically contrary to movement politics.
Movement politics says, me, I'm the defendant, or me, I'm the one who they're after.
I've got to say so, and you're the lawyer, and I want you to do what I tell you to do.
Don't tell me I can't talk, or don't tell me I have to dress this way or that, but help me.
But don't try to

say you're going to make the final decision because you're not i mean if you're not going to help me then i'll get somebody else and that was a problem that we were trying to overcome we were having problems getting enough lawyers that would do the legal work on a reasonable basis but we had a good legal conference i think it had a big impact and it is documented in the observer other big events of course
For a street demonstration, I guess it was the early 70s.
I can't ever remember dates.
All I remember is kind of the flow of events.
You know, Nixon got in, Nixon got re-elected, and they're always lying to you.

I mean, they're going to negotiate, and they're going to get out, and this is a step, and then you find out they've invaded Cambodia, and they're bombing this, and they're doing all this shit they don't want to tell you about.
And we had a major demonstration night with 20, 25,000 people in the streets of Austin, which is, that's lots of people for the size of this city at that time.
The number of demonstrations out at the university would have 10 to 15,000 people there.
That makes the establishment figures very nervous.
Whenever that many people who are upset, some of whom are very angry, some of whom are unstable.
And a lot of them very intense and committed.
Most of them are not unstable.
I don't know if you ever get that notion, but that's not true.
But some are, and you'll get crazy things happen.

You have demonstrations where, at that point in time, I don't know, they may have changed the law on this now, where it's not illegal for me to carry a torch and put rags on the end of a stick, put gasoline, light it, and walk down the street at night.

Well, you think about it, if you're the chancellor of the university and you're going to have 500 people out there and you're going to have a torchlight parade around your house in the middle of the night, that makes you nervous.
You might get your house burned down.
And if you concentrate on the economic institutions, all of this was happening around the country.
I mean, the intensity level was going up.
The property was starting to get destroyed.
The pressure was going on.
Bombs were going off.
Buildings were being burned up.
capitalism had to make some adjustments.
Plus the military wasn't wanting to fight.
I'm not talking about the fucking officers, fuck them.
They just do what they're told generally, but the men didn't want to fight.
So they knew they had to, they lost their war.
They had to get out.
What else did we have?
Major event in Austin, the first and probably the second farm workers march.
coming from the valley, I forget how long it took, but probably a month or six weeks where the group of farm workers started marching up here, and it culminated in a big march down Congress Avenue.
It started out of St. Edwards, which is about five, six, seven miles out in South Austin, and it came up to the state capitol.
And there must have been 15,000 or 20,000 people, and that was about a minimum wage.
Farm workers were not covered by it.
by minimum wage, and they were getting screwed bad, still are for that matter.
That was a major event.
We had at one point an event I thought worked well because one of the tensions always was whether you focus on a single issue or whether you take on several issues.
And of course, if you're revolutionary or radical, you understand the connections between events.
There is a connection between poverty, the war, and racism.
There's certain interests
that look at those things in a certain way and want them, you know, things to happen a certain way.
So we did it at one point, most of the time whenever a big anti-war thing would come along, it'd be pretty much a single focus.
And a lot of years of the anti-war thing, of course this is when all across the country the same process is going on.
More and more people are seeing the relationship between these different issues.
Then they would also mention
racism and poverty and Chicano sexism.
All of this would come up and what kind of banners are you going to have?
What kind of signs are you going to have?
Who are the speakers going to be?
How long are you going to let them speak?
Who's going to speak first?
Who's going to speak last?
If you know the dynamics of meetings, you know there are certain benefits.
There are certain benefits to be first, last, or in the middle.
And we finally had a...
A demonstration here, I don't know how many, 3, 4, 5,000 people, called We the People, where it was multifaceted.
I mean, it hit about 8 or 10 issues.
A lot of the local neighborhood groups who never had any organized way of participating got into that because it was a mass public protest about we don't like the way things are.
and we the people are going to say something about it, and I don't know whether you're going to do anything about it, but we're going to say we don't like it.
And that worked out pretty well, and it helped get us away from the single focus.
The Trotskyists always wanted to just talk about the war.
Don't talk about this, don't talk about that, just talk about the war.
And, of course, most of the new left people and the American friends didn't want to do that.
They wanted to talk about more than just the war.

major civil rights.

B.T.

Bonner, who was a black man organizer with the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, Martin Luther King's outfit, helped organize some major civil rights demonstrations in Huntsville, Texas, which a number of us from Austin went over to support.

In your opinion, is the art of practicing law immoral?
Why?
And why not be a people's lawyer like Ralph Nader or work for the ACLU?
The first part of it was what?
Is the art of practicing law immoral?
And what was the next phrase?
Oh, and why?
No, I don't think it's immoral.
Of course, I have some problems with the whole notion of morality.
I mean...
We're not careful.
We get off into religious philosophies and all that.
I don't believe in that shit either.
I believe we have to decide what's right and wrong and basically good for people.
So in that sense, I consider myself a very moral person.
I think that practicing law, you can be a moral person.
I don't think that lawyers who have good convictions and good principles find it very difficult.
If you look at what the body of the laws are,
In our society, they're to protect property rights and business relationships primarily.
The people who go to prison, contrary to what most people think, are not murderers and rapists.
I don't know what the figures are.
Seventy-five to ninety percent of them are crimes against property.
Somebody that stole something or tried to steal something or a burglar or that kind of thing.
And I don't believe that.
I don't believe that's a crime.
Now, a crime to me is that Rockefeller, that son of a bitch is a fucking criminal.
He's got more money than he could possibly use, and he doesn't do people any good.
People starve to death, and he's sitting on top of a whole lot of money.
Fuck him.
And that's a crime.
Lawyers have to deal with that all the time.
I mean, they're defending...
They have to...
appear before judges and play a certain game, or they get thrown into jail themselves or get thrown out of court.

You tell a judge, I think you're a liar, I know how you got to be a judge, I don't think you can possibly give a fair decision in this or any other case, which is, if you know how judges are selected, as I do, it's true in nine times of the cases, they gave money or they did this favor or that favor, and that's how they got to be judges.
So lawyers have to deal with that all the time.

You have to deal with district attorneys who are mostly sleazy, young, ambitious people who've been fed a bunch of goodies about how they can make a name for themselves prosecuting these heinous criminals.
They're never smart enough to realize that Rockefeller's a criminal, not the fellow who's trying to steal for his family.
